**Chapter 25 of the *Viṣṇu Smṛti* outlines the duties (*dharmāḥ*) of women (*strīṇāṃ*), including a specific prescription for a widow.**[^1]

The chapter opens:  
> Now, the duties of women.[^2]

It lists general duties such as:  
> To follow the same vows as her husband;  
> To honor her mother-in-law, father-in-law, preceptor, deities, and guests;  
> To keep her household utensils well-ordered;  
> Not to be open-handed;  
> To keep her vessels well-guarded;  
> Not to be fond of black magic;  
> To be devoted to auspicious practices;  
> When her husband is away, not to adorn herself;  
> Not to go to others' houses;  
> Not to stand at the door or in windows;  
> Not to be independent in any act;  
> To be dependent on her father, husband, or son, in childhood, youth, and old age.[^3]

Specifically on widowhood:  
> When her husband is dead, to practice chastity or to ascend the funeral pyre after him.[^4]

The chapter concludes:  
> A virtuous woman who, after her husband's death, remains established in chastity,  
> Goes to heaven, even if she is sonless, like those who are celibate students.[^5]

> For women there is no separate sacrifice, no vow, nor any fast;  
> The husband whom she serves, by that she is glorified in heaven.[^6]

No other chapters in the *Viṣṇu Smṛti* provide additional details on widow duties (e.g., no extended rules on maintenance, remarriage, or rituals specific to widows beyond chastity/sati). Chapter 17 touches on inheritance rights ("The property of a man without a son goes to his wife"), but not duties.[^7]

